column168: On 4/7 the shipper brought 2 pieces to AA Cargo @ JFK for transport to AUA.  The shipment was processed for receipt and the customer left.  A strong odor was noticed from one of the boxes.  Because of the odor, the shipper was notified on 4/7 on the day shift to advise the box contained items the were possibly dangerous goods and nothing was declared on the paperwork received.  The airwaybill stated this shipment machine parts.  The shipment was staged in our cage.  When the customer came in, the box was opened and it was found that there were 4 aerosol containers of paint along with a flashlight and other machine pts.  The customer reclaimed the machine parts and left the box and the inner packaging at AA Cargo, where it remins at this time.  FAA was called and they came in and inspected on 4/8.
column169: No changes were made at American Airlines Cargo as our personel acted in accordance to all rules and regulations and because of their vigilance the incident was found prior to loading and transportation.

column168: While parked at the Veolia 10-day intransit facility in Port Arthur, TX, a dry van was found to be dripping liquid from the bottom/middle part of the van.  The van was temporarily remediated in order to move it across the street into the Veolia permitted facility where the leaking container could be safely handled and prepared for disposal.  A crew of six Veolia hazmat employees managed the cleanup at the temporary 10-day intransit yard where the van had been parked.  Upon arrival at the Veolia disposal facility, a crew donning Level C PPE began removing drums from the shipment to retrieve the leaking container.  A leaking 20 gallon white poly drum was identified with most of the liquid leaked from it.  It was discovered that the drum had a nail-sized hole at the bottom of it.  The drum was flipped upside down to stop the leak and then overpacked.  The van was cleaned with hidry until all visible signs of waste were removed.  It appears the direct cause was the small hole in the bottom of the drum that might have been caused from the loading of the van or the load shifting during transport.  The generator was contacted to discuss possible prevention of reoccurance.  Veolia environmental personnel were contacted to make notifications/reports to the TCEQ.   The van was pressure washed to remove acid from inside the van floor and the under carriage.
column169: The local Veolia operations teams have been reminded to inspect all pallets for nails, etc. prior to loading.

column168: It was reported that a purple material is leaking from the trailer.  It is known that there are UN1719, UN1993, UN2922, and UN3266 on board the trailer.  After speaking with the driver I have found that there the material has not dripped onto the ground and the release is contianed within the trailer.   The Kansas City fire department and hazmat team is now on site.  KC Fire Dept/Hazmat has assumed control of the scene at this time.  They have decided that they would like to be the first to enter the leaking trailer.  Since there is no MSDS sheet with the driver, the hazmat team will be sampling via a HazCat kit.  Once the material has been determined, the network contractor will then be allowed to assess the situation.   The contractor has indicated that the material released is High Shine Purple Dressing UN1993 PGII Class 3.The damaged container was 3 rows back from the trailer door and had released material over the trailer floor.  Given that the released material was a class 8 the floor needed to be washed down.  The trailer contents were removed and the floor was cleaned.  The network contractor indicated that it seemed that the package was loaded damaged.  On the bottom of the container there appeared what seemed to be a razor cut.  No waste has been generated as the materials reclaimed will be combined with other waste for fuel reclamation.

column168: During an outbound train inspection in the railyard, entrained UTLX 203068 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was observed with a fresh product stain on its side shell. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected UTLX 203068. The responder reported that product was emanating from under the sealed valve housing cover. Seal numbered 110272 was removed and the valves were inspected. Product drips were noticed emanating from the closed threaded liquid valve at the valve base. The valve was 1/2 turn less than tool tight at the threaded base. The liquid valve assembly was tool tightened and the product drips ceased. Afterwards, the attached liquid valve handle would not fit under the housing cover during closure attempts of the housing cover. The liquid valve handle was removed and secured within the valve housing cover. All spillage that did not evaporate was wiped. No ground impact from this product release was evident. UTLX 203068 was released to proceed to its destination at 1245 hrs. MDT, 4/14/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Misrouted GATX 200577 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported emanating a product odor and observed with a fresh product stain on its side shell during normal switching operations in the railyard. No product impacted the ground. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 200577 and reported finding only one of eight manway securement bolts applied and it was less than tool tight (finger loose). The responder properly applied and tool tightened all the manway securement bolts. No further product release was observed during subsequent movements in the railyard. All spillage on the side shell evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: UTLX 67814 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car) on the BNSF Barstow railyard one spot repair track for side ladder defect repairs was reported emanating a residue product odor. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected UTLX 67814. The responder reported all seals were intact, except no seal was found on the valve's protective housing cover due to a defective locking pin. All eight manway cover securement bolts were 1/2 to 3/4 turns less than tool tight. The liquid line and vapor closure plugs were two turns less than tool tight with both valves being closed. The responder properly tool tightened all manway securement bolts and the closure plugs. All securement was completed by 1345 hrs. PDT, 4/08/08 and the product odor emanating from UTLX 67814 ceased. No liquid product release was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported TILX 290308 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with a product splash onto its tank shell during movement in the railyard. TILX 290308 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard, awaiting a detailed inspection. BNSF contract responders inspected TILX 290308 the morning of 4/06/08 and determined that the product release emanated from the 75 psi pressure relief device (PRD). Preliminary inspection of the PRD revealed no visual defects. The secured manway lid was opened and responders noted two inches of product outage inside TILX 290308; therefore concluding that TILX 290308 was in an overfilled condition which caused the PRD to expel liquid product during movement. On 4/07/08, the BNSF contractor assisted the shipper in reducing 983 gallons of product into a tank truck via the bottom outlet valve without further incident. The contract responders disassembled the PRD, cleaned and reversed the PRD O-rings since the face of one O-ring had some flat spots. The reassembled PRD was tested using a nitrogen blanket induced inside TILX 290308 with no vapor release observed at the internal pressure of 20 psi. The spillage on TILX 290308 was wiped and it was released to proceed to its destination by approximately 1415 hrs. MDT, 4/07/08. No ground impact from this product release was evident.

column168: The driver traveled highway I25S to Highway 50 W headed for Salida. At 8:30am, at highway mile marker 231, the drivers wheels left the highway on the curbside and when the driver notice this he over corrected and lost control of the vehicle. This caused the vehicle to begin to tip against the guard rail; this cut the straps securing the load. The load of cylinders then was spilled off the trailer all along the road and down the side of the mountain. We had 6 of the spilled cylinders rolling down the side of the mountain enter the Arkansas River. The road was closed for 15 hours while the clean up happened.

column168: On April 4, 2008, a Werner Enterprises driver while checking his load at a rest stop observed paint leaking at the rear of the trailer.  A private response team was dispatched to the incident.  Upon arrival, the response team determined that 1 tote of a load of 10 totes was leaking due to a faulty valve. The product (Strontium Chromate Dispersion) was a paint related material, UN1263. The response team removed all of the totes, repaired the valve, cleaned all of the totes and cleaned the trailer.  No product was released out of the trailer.  All waste was containerized into a drum for disposal at a permitted facility.
column169: Driver should check to see that the load is properly braced and blocked and all valves at closed and secured.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading, an internal valve developed a leak. Personnel from the consignee, Reichhold, Inc. performed the cleanup using neutralizer and absorbent material.  Reichhold, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Slay Transportation CO., Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line with 15 hazardous items (listed below), on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel New York Express from Long Beach, California to Kobe, Japan.    - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Ethyl Acetate, Modified Acrylic Acid), Class 3, FP 22C, PG II  - UN1173, Ethyl Acetate, Class 3, FP 22, PG II  - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Acetone), Class 3, FP -15.5C, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Ethyl Methacrylate, Ethylene Glycol Dimethacrylate), Class 3, FP 19.9C, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Acetone, Nitromethane), Class 3, FP -17.2, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN2531, Methacrylic Acid, Stabilized, Class 8, PG II  - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Isopropyl Alcohol, 2-Propanol), Class 3, FP -17.2C, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN1263, Paint, Class 3, FP 12.7C, PG II  - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Ethyl Methacrylate), Class 3, FP 43C, PG III  - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Isopropyl Alcohol), Class 3, FP 19.9C, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Acetone, Ethyl Acetate), Class 3, FP -17.2C, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Methyl Ethyl Ketone, Isopropyl Alcohol), Class 3, FP -9.9C, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Isobutyl Acetate, Ethyl Acetate), Class 3, FP 19.9C, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN1090, Acetone Solutions, Class 3, FP -16.6C, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS, Class 3, FP -17.2C, PG II, Ltd Qty    OOCL advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed from Long Beach of additional hazardous material ((UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS (Ethyl Acetate, Isopropyl Alcohol), Class 3, FP 37.7C, PG III)) in the container that was not original booked or otherwise identified.    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the additional hazardous material.    The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.

column168: While departing Nalco, driver stopped for RR crossing when he heard drums fall over.  He then fouund that the two drums loaded had falled over and one had released it contents through out the straight truck.  Nalco responded and contained the spill to the truck and surrounding area.  Inland Waters responded to clean up spill.  Due to no one actually seeing the containers and how damaged but Nalco, it is unknown if top, side, or bottom failed.
column169: Pitt Ohio has been making pick ups at this location for years.  It is a dock that the shipper loads the freight and then secures it in the back of the unit.  They then go back to the driver, give paperwork and driver departs.  Everytime this has happened.  Unfortunately, the shipper did not secure these two drums and they fell over in transit resulting in a 55 gallon spill.      Drivers have been alerted that regardless of who loads, before departing location, he/she must see the load and secure such.

column168: A VEOLIA EMPLOYEE WAS STARTING TO OFFLOAD TOTES FROM A SERVICE TRUCK ONTO THE STORAGE TRAILER THAT WAS LOCATED AT THE VEOLIA 10 DAY INTRANSIT FACILITY LOCATED IN CULPEPER, VA WHEN HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK. THE TOTE WAS OBSERVED TO HAVE A PIN SIZED HOLE APX 3/4 THE WAY UP THE TOTE ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID TO SPILL TO THE FLOOR OF THE VEHICLE. THERE WAS NO RELEASE TO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT. THE MATERIAL WAS PUMPED OFF INTO A NEW TOTE BY VEOLIA EMPLOYEES AND THE OLD DAMAGED TOTE WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL AT A PERMITTED DISPOSAL FACILITY.

column42: OXYGEN GENERATOR, CHEMICAL (INCLUDING WHEN CONTAINED IN ASSOCIATED EQUIPMENT, E.G., PASSENGER SERVICE UNITS (PSUS), PORTABLE BREATHING EQUIPMENT (PBE), ETC).
column168: On 4-17-08 at approximately 2:50pm one of our front load garbage trucks, with a full load, was fueling at our facility. The driver heard a “popping” noise coming from the hopper, he moved away from the truck to investigate.  The driver and two other employees noticed smoke billowing from the hopper.     Immediately he discontinued fueling the truck and moved the truck approximately 40 feet away from the fueling station and offloaded the waste that was in the truck onto a concrete slab.    The area that was on fire was near the cab of the truck, which means that it was one of the last loads placed into the truck. Immediately water was applied to the burning area. It was noticed that there was one metal cylinder that was the cause of the fire.     After removing the metal cylinder the load was spread out to search for more. A total of 6 cylinders were located. The markings are Scott, Oxygen Generating, Serial numbers 00023928, 00023927, 00023931, 00023952, 00023920, the unit that burnt no longer had any markings. Fearing further fires all of the units were placed into a drum of water.    After a brief internet search it was clear that these units are aviation oxygen generating units. Phone calls were immediately made to the DOT, FAA, TSA, and ultimately to the Department Homeland Security to find someone to report this to. In the end the Federal Aviation Administration Office of Security and Hazardous Materials office was reached.     On 4-18-08 at approximately 9:00am David Murphy and Kevin Fitzpatrick of the US Department of Transportation Federal Aviation Administration Office of Security and Hazardous Materials arrived. They took statements and said that the investigation on the dumping of these unites would start.    On 4-21-08 at approximately 11:00am the two investigators mentioned above along with Bob Burns and Sean Lynum from the US Department of Transportation Pipeline & Hazardous Materials Safety Administration continued the investigation.    As of the time of this report, no one has been able to confirm how they units will be disposed.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: During an inbound railcar interchange inspection in the railyard, GATX 22283 was reported with a slow product drip emanating from the bottom outlet cap (BOC). GATX 22283 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with a receptacle placed under the BOC to catch drippage. BNSF contract responders and a BNSF mechanical responder inspected GATX 22283 finding the top operated bottom outlet valve's (TOBOV) operating rod in a partial open position. Responders closed the TOBOV, taking two full turns to do so. Also, the BOC was found less than tool tight. During the tightening of the BOC, responders reported some resistance; but once it was tightened beyond the threaded area of resistance, an additional 3-4 turns fully tool tightened the BOC. After securement was completed by 1730 hrs. CDT, 4/03/08, product drips ceased. The spillage collected in the catch receptacle (approximately two gallons) was neutralized. No ground impact was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: An over speed coupling in the BNSF hump yard resulted in UTLX 12425 expelling a small amount of product from its pressure relief device (PRD) due to the ensuing internal liquid hydraulic pressure surge. A BNSF mechanical responder inspected UTLX 12425 finding the PRD in working order and no other securement issues. The product spillage atop UTLX 12425 and around its PRD was water diluted. No ground impact from this event was evident.

column168: FILE- 08-22 FAA & DOT SHIPPER- UNITED STATES AIR FORCE- TMO AWB#- AUF 1258058992 OKC                                                                                   ON 04/02/2008 AT 1442, A LEAKING AND ODOROUS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN "A" BUILDING, LOCATED ATTHE DHL MAIN SORT FACILITY, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. SPILL TECHNICIANS TERRY RUGGERIE AND ELWOOD BOHL DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND EMITTING A GAS ODOR. THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN A FUEL CONTROL WITH RESIDUAL FUEL STILL INSIDE. DUE TO THE FUEL NOT BEING PROPERLY DRAINED AND PREPARED FOR TRANSPORTATION, A TOTAL OF 2 OZ OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT # 387, ASTAR. THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE GREAT LAKES REGION FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL   CLEAR OF SCENE: 1537.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

REY FROM THE RIVERSIDE COUNTY REGIONAL HUB REPORTED THAT THEY HAD A LEAKING SHIPMENT WITH AN ODOR OF GASOLINE. THE HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND EMITTING A KEROSENE ODOR. THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN A 165,000 BTU KEROSENE HEATER WITH RESIDUAL FUEL INSIDE. DUE TO THE SHIPMENT LEAKING THROUGH THE VENTED CLOSURE AND NOT BEING DRAINED!  PROPERLY PREPARED FOR TRANSPORTATION, A TOTAL OF 1 GALLON OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO THE RIVERSIDE COUNTY REGIONAL HUB VIA TRUCK # 6267.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0524 EST.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was received for unloading at the intended waste disposal facility.  Upon opening the rear door, it was noticed that a small box on the rear was saturated with liquid which had leaked onto the floor and rear bumper of the trailer.  Facility personnel immediately donned the appropriate protective equipment and moved the box into a drum to prevent further spillage.  The response crew cleaned up the area with a suitable absorbent material and loaded it into a suitable container for proper disposal.  It was determined that a 1 liter glass bottle inside the box had broken.  The shipment was then disposed of at the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The box containing the glass containers was improperly stowed on the trailer, causing a one liter glass container inside to break. The shipper was also advised to use better inner packing when shipping glass containers.

The Allegeheny Valley RR Trainmaster, advised that the car was isolated at Glenwood Yard, Pittsburgh, PA. As the consignee, Transflo Terminal Services, was located within Glenwood Yard, they were contacted for assistance. Transflo Terminal Services personnel reported 2 of 8 manway cover bolts less than tool tight. The leak was secured and the car released for transportation.  Cause Code: 200  NARRI:  5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column168: On April 12, 2008 at 22:26 personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard discovered TILX 192505, a loaded tank car of Alchols, N.O.S leaking from the bottom outlet. The car was isolated and Cumberland Fire Department, Poet Biorefining, and Maryland Dept. of Environment were notified. Specialized Professional Services Inc. a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the bottom operating handle was not properly secured and the bottom outlet cap was loose. Contractor personnel closed the bottom outlet handle and secured the safety pin and applied a seal. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.    Cause Code: 551  NARRI:  5(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On April 17, 2008 at 12:17 hours, the CSX Transpotation Yardmaster in New Castle, PA reported loaded tank car GATX 6327, Sulphuric Acid, leaking from its top. CSX Transportation dispatched Specialized Professional Services, Incorporated (SPSI), Washington, PA to the scene. SPSI personnel advised the leak was at the liquid line and its closure cap. SPSI personnel relieved the pressure in the tank anfd the leak ceased. After inspecting the liquid line and its closure cap, the gasket for the closure cap was found to be defective. The gasket was replaced it in kind and the fitting secured. SPSI personnel cleaned the side of the tank and collected impacted materials, and the car was released for transportation.    NARRI: 5(5 + 5 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 100  Cause Code: 249

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A CARTON CONTAINING A PAIL OF PAINT WAS PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT BLADE. THE AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED SALVAGE DRUMS. THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A LINED SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OFCHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALSI PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MW PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: Traveling on I-635 Westbound, driver heard movement in his trailer, and noticed material leaking from trailer.  Driver pulled to the shoulder of the highway, and determined leak was coming from trailer.  Fire, police, Univar managmement personnel arrived at the scene.  Representatives from City of Dallas public works, TXDOT, and EPA also arrived.  Fire department used absorbent materials to contain the flow of material.  Independent hazmat response team was contracted by Unviar to respond, clean, and remediate the spill.  Containers from trailer were decontaminated along with the trailer itself.  Material from failed container was transferred into another suitable container. Cleaned materials were placed in another Univar trailer and both trailers returned to Univar facility.  Emergency response contractor removed contaminated soil for disposal, and replaced.  This cleanup plan was reviewed and approved by the City of Dallas and EPA representatives.      Incident was determined to be caused by failure of load locking bar inside trailer.  When bar failed, it caused the IBC to shift inside the trailer.  The IBC struck the front wall of the trailer, and cracked along the side corner.
column169: Load locking bars and all load securement devices will be inspected before use and any devices in need of repair will be serviced or removed from use.  Review also done of securement practices to insure best available devices are available and selected.

column168: The shipment was offered to Hapag-Lloyd from Houston, Texas on the Westfalia Express as non-hazardous cargo.    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed from Houston on undeclared hazardous material loaded in the container.    The shipping papers that accompanied the container did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials, and the container was not placarded and/or marked.    The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column168: CREW WAS TYING ON TO TRAIN THAT WAS LEFT BY BNSF RAILWAY, TRAIN#MGALIHB313 AND WHILE RELEASING HAND BRAKES ON TRAIN OBSERVED RAIL CAR UTLX 210934 LEAKING LIQUID FROM VALVE DOME. CREW SUBSEQUENTLY CONTACTED INDIANA HARBOR BELT (IHB) OPERATIONS CENTER WHO CONTACTED CHIEF MECHANICAL OFFICERR AND THIS WRITER WHO IS HAZMAT OFFICER. PRODUCE WAS DESCRIBED AS UN 1987 ALCOHOL NOS. UPON ARRIVAL OF CHIEF MECHANICAL OFFICER AND ME WE VERIFIED SOURCE OF LEAK AND CONTACTED HAZMAT CONTRACTOR, "SUN PRO"  SERVICES WHO ARIVED ON SCENE AND WITH WRITER OPENED VALVE DOME AND OBSEVERVED THAT LIQUID INDUCTION LINE VALVE WAS OPENED APPROXIMATELY 1/8"  AND NNOT CLOSED PROPERLY. ADDITIONALLY WE NOTED THAT CAP ON LIQUID INDUCTION VALVED WAS LOOSE AND WAS ONLY HAND TIGHTENED WHICH WAS SOURCE OF LEAK. LIQUID INDUCTION VALVE CAP WAS WRENCH TIGHTENED AND VALVE COCK CLOSED WHICH STOPPED LEAK. WE APPLIED SEAL TO DOME UNDER SEAL #SUNPRO 40582. column168: On Monday 4/21 at 6:30 AM EST, Transfer Operator - Anthony Marinaccio was setting up to conduct a Marsulex Fresh Sulfuric Acid (H2SO4) tank car -to- tank truck transfer; the transfer was scheduled to originate from tank car PROX 60114 and load 48,000 LBS into Contract Chemical Carrier's (CCC) trailer 181.  When doing so the employee failed to check whether the tank car's primary and secondary liquid product fitting valves were in the closed position, prior to pressurizing the tank car.  The Mr. Marinaccio then proceeded to establish connections on the trailer's end (e.g., apply loading tube and apply the transfer hose), when doing so the H2SO4 Acid then began to discharge from the transfer hose uninhibited and Mr. Marinaccio was splashed when the H2SO4 deflected off the side of the CCC trailer.  The H2SO4 Acid came into contact with Mr. Marinaccio's chin area and the back of his neck.  Once the employee was splashed with acid, he panicked and immediately descended from the transfer rack without shutting off either the tank car's product valve and the air pressure going into the tank car.  Another Transfer Operator - Greg Hepfer who was working in the vicinity on another transfer track heard the commotion and immediately donned this PPE and proceeded to investigate the situation; Mr. Hepfer made the radio call to alert the his fellow team members of the spill and immediately went up to the top of the car and saw that the product (primary & secondary) valves were in fact in the open position.  Mr. Hepfer then immediately closed the valves and the product began to stop discharging.  Mr. Hepfer then proceeded to rinse off the CCC trailer and establish the trailer connection to purge the residual product from the transfer lines.   By 7:00, facility's Emergency Response Plan was fully activated, and onsite personnel then began the process of containing and remediation the spill, by utilizing sodium bicarbonate to neutralize and dike off the spillage.  The National Response Center and PADEP were notified of the incident and Emergency Response/Environmental Contractor - React Environmental handled the cleanup efforts and removal of ballast.  Approximately 250 Gallons of Sulfuric Acid spilled on the CCC trailer #181, asphalt aisle way in between transfer tracks # 2 and three, corresponding ballast and also onto two adjacent DuPont TiO2 tank cars ACFX 71636, DUPX 80238.      Mr. Marinaccia sustained a 2nd degree chemical burn to the back of the back of his neck; and was treated and evaluated the physician at Concentra Medical Center located at 7000 Holstein Ave Philadelphia, PA   19153 (215) 365-7510.  Mr. Marinaccia was prescribed a pain medication and was released back to full duty the proceeding day (Tuesday 4/22).
column169: • The involved employee shall be disciplined (e.g., company performance improvement process) for his negligence in complying with standard operating procedures for transferring Sulfuric Acid from tank car -to- tank truck.    • Savage's Management shall evaluate the present skills and knowledge of Philadelphia's operational staff to ensure that individuals are complying with the applicable transfer procedures.    • Savage shall accelerate the implementation of their operating procedural (administrative; transfer; equipment) training program, this includes: educating the employees on the specific standards and steps in the procedure; administer procedural exams and proficiency/competency exercises.  The facility was previously operated by Kinder Morgan Materials Services and Savage took over operations effective April 1, 2008.

LANGER TRANSPORT DELIVERED A LOAD OF MONDUR 541 LIGHT TO MASONITE IN WAHPETON, NORTH DAKOTA. THE DRIVER COMPLETED THE OFF LOADING PROCESS AND BLEW OUT HIS LINES. HE THEN DISCONNECTED HIS HOSE FROM THE TRAILER AND RESTED IT ON THE TRAILER. THE VALVE AT THE CUSTOMERS STORAGE TANK WAS LEFT OPEN AND A FEW MOMENTS LATER PRODUCT FLOWED BACK THROUGH THE HOSE AND SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRIVER CALLED CHEMTREC AND THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP. AFTER AN INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED BECAUSE OF OPERATOR ERROR.
column169: THE DRIVER WILL BE BROUGHT BACK INTO THE TERMINAL FOR RETRAINING. HE WILL BE SHOWN THE PROPER WAY TO DISCONNECT HOSES AND THE IMPORTANCE OF CAPPING EACH HOSE BEFORE IT IS PUT DOWN. PART OF THE PROCESS WHEN DISCONNECTING HOSES INCLUDES ENSURING THAT THE VALVE ON THE CUSTOMER'S END IS CLOSED. THIS EVEN WILL BE DISCUSSED AT OUR NEXT SAFETY AND USED AS A LEARNING TOOL THROUGHOUT THE COMPANY.

column168: Driver arrived at Rayne Truck Unload Station and parked unit @ the #1 (east) unload header - Driver connected ground pump and started pump - Driver then connected truck pump and engaged truck gear pump - Employee checked all connections for leaks and vent for vacuum - He stood @ controls and verified Titan readout was counting down - He observed 5 barrels being removed from trailer - Walked over to containment bucket and rechecked connection for leak sand found none - Due to a slight misty rain he then positioned himself in the stationary shelter - At 25 barrels on the Titanread out, he observed the containment bucket over filling - Employee shut down pump and reported spill to Dispatch. He was instructed not to remove gear pump hose until his Supervisor arrived. He laid down sorbet pads to start clean up process and dammed up area with shovel.At 6:30 p.m. I arrived on location and had him remove hose from the connection - The 3" gasket was found to be bad and was split at both points were the ears are positioned.
column169: Instruct all drivers to use 12 & 6 o'clock method of securing hose ears, Implement a requirement for all driver to check all connections at 3-5 minutes intervals, Develop a weekly maintenance schedule and have dispatch control and log results.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon inspection of the trailer, at the Triple Crown Services' facility in Chicago, Illinois, a leak was discovered.  Triple Crown Services personnel applied absorbent material to the trailer floor, and placed a catch pan outside the trailer to prevent migration.  SET Environmental, Inc. of Bridgeview, Illinois was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, SET Environmental, Inc. began to offload the trailer.  Thirteen (13) totes were located inside the trailer.  One (1) tote was discovered with a loose bung.  Approximately one gallon of free product was released.  SET Environmental Inc. proceeded to pressure wash the affected trailer following offload, and transferred the damaged tote into two (2) smaller totes.  SET Environmental Inc. also scraped the dirt surface beneath the trailer, which had been affected during wash out.  One (1) 55-gallon drum of rinse water, and two (2) 55-gallon drums of soil, absorbents, and PPE were generated during the cleanup.  The trailer was reloaded and sent on to its destination.  SET Environmental, Inc. coordinated disposal of the three (3) 55-gallon drums, in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a loose bung on the tote, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Triple Crown Services will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: On April 11th at 02:24 hours, personnel in the CSXT Augusta Yard discovered PLCX22090, a residue tank car of Cyclohexone Solution, hissing from the top of car.  The area around the rail car was isolated.  Chemtrec (report number 2008-04-11-00030) assisted in contacting the shipper, DSM Chemicals North America.  DSM dispatched a response crew to the scene and found that the container was releasing nitogen and possibly cyclohexanone vapors from the manway cover gasket area.  DSM personnel advised that they pressurize the car with nitrogen when off loading at their facility.  DSM  personnel opened the manway cover to inspect the gasket for defects.  After taking no exceptions, they closed the cover, and properly tightened the fasteners.  The car was tested for securement then released to destination.  Approximately one pound of vapor was released into the atmosphere.  Cause Code:  200  NARRI = 5(4+1+0) x (2+0) = 50
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On April 15, 2008 at 11:44, personnel in the CSXT CovingtonYard discovered WACX 151213, a loaded tank car of Phosphoric Acid, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was located in the middle of the classification yard. Virginia EOC, PCS Sales, Meadewestvaco, Chemtrec and the NRC were notified. WEL Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom wash out leaking approximately 3 to 5 gallons per minute. CSXT contacted Meadewetsvaco, who supplied an empty rail car to transload the product from the leaking tank car. Once the product was transloaded, it was the determined that the gasket on the bottom washout blind flange had deteriorated, causing the leak.    Cause Code:  641  NARRI:  5(5+3+0) X (5+0) = 200

column168: On April 23, 2008 at 09:00, personnel in the CSXT Barr Yard  discovered SHPX206803, a loaded tank car of spent sulfuric acid, leaking from top of car. The car was isolated and Marsulex, Chemtrec, the Riverdale Fire Department, National Response Center and Illinois EMA were notified (CHEMTREC Report #2008-0423-00083, NRC report # 868821, IL EMA report # H2008-0537). SunPro Environmental Services, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the 4 bolt flange on the top of the liquid line leaking.  Sunpro personnel tightened the flange and observed leaking product from the bottom of the modified spool piece after the bolts were made tight.  All bolts were secured and tool tight.  A pressure gauge was placed on the vapor line and found pressure steady at 2 psi. Contractor personnel decontaminated the car and immediate ground area of spilled material. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 113  NARRI:  2 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT  OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE  COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: Javier Rodriguez, Pacific Rail Ramp Manager, observed an unknown amount of placarded corrosive liquid was releasing from the bottom of bulletined BONU 924390 at the Intermodal ramp in Avondale, LA. No injuries or waterways were involved. The liquid was described as clear and had a strong odor. Mr. Rodriguez stated the outbound load was still releasing at a rate of one-half gallon per hour. The amount on the ground and the cause were unknown. Mr. Rodriguez advised a ten-inch puddle of product pooled on the dirt. Tom Robinson, Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified, stated he would follow up with Mr. Rodriguez, advised a contractor would be dispatched, and requested RMCC notify Thomas Carmichael, Senior Special Agent, to provide site security until the contractor arrived. Agent Carmichael was notified stated he would investi9ate the incident, and advised he would follow up with Mr. Rodriguez. State regulatory agencies were notified within the prescribed time parameters.   UPDATE: At 10:42 AM, Tom Robinson,   Manager of Hazardous Materials, was contacted, stated the bulletined was isolated, and advised he was en route with a two hour ETA.   Mr. Robinson further stated United States Environmental Services, Contractor, was en route with a one hour ETA. Mr. Robinson advised the release did not appear to be due to damage to the bulktainer. Mr. Robinson requested RMCC have the shipper contact him. John Stein, Chemtrec, was notified and stated the shipper would contact Mr. Robinson. UPDATE: At 01 :10 PM, Tom Robinson.   Manager of Hazardous Materials advised he was on scene, estimated that approximately one gallon of product was on the ground, and the release was contained and slowed to a drip. Mr. Robinson further advised the container was missing the external bottom outlet valve and a contractor was searching for a new valve.   UPDATE: At 05:11 PM, Tom Robinson, Manager of Hazardous Materials,   advised there was no leak from the bottom just a dripping of condensation, and the leak on the top was repaired by changing gaskets   on the valve flanges and properly closing the butterfly valve. Mr. Robinson advised all released product was remediated and no further actions were required.

column168: Trailer 317-6651 arrived in from the UPW FAC with a strong chemical odor eminating from it before it was opened. The Trailer was immediately pulled out to the yard and door opened for ventilation. Saety Manager Jeff Turner,CHEMTREC, and the shipper where all contacted. NRC Environmental was called in to handle the spill & clean up.  NRC Report:  NRC Environmental Services (NRCES) was called by Conway Freight to a possible flammable liquid spill in the back of a Conway Freight trailer (3176651) April 11, 2008. Conway Freight personnel noticed a strong odor in the trailer as it was being unloaded. NRCES was called to investigate the source of the odor and clean up any spill if necessary.  NRCES used Level C PPE and a four-gas meter during the investigation of the odor. NRCES found that one, five-gallon pail of Carboline #2 Thinner (Flammable Liquid) was damaged and had leaked an estimated two to three gallons of material. NRCES overpacked the damaged pail of material. NRCES then re-palletized the rest of the material that was on the pallet. The material that had spilled from the drum had evaporated shortly after leaking from the pail. NRCES will dispose of the overpack drum of material when all of the proper profile and waste manifest paperwork is completed.

column168: At 01:55, a supervisor noticed flames coming from a package moving on a conveyor belt in the building. He reported the fire to other management in the building, who called in a Plant Engineering mechanic. The P.E. mechhanic directed Jared Halstead , supervisor to a fire extinguisher. Jared put out the fire with a dry chemical fire extinguisher. Investigation revealed a hole in one of 12 1-quart cans of PVC primer, as a cause of a leak in the package. It is believed that vapors from the leak were ignited by static electricity generated by the conveyor equipment.

column168: Driver was parked in truck stop parking lot staying in nearby hotel. During the night fire department got a call complaining of an odor something like burning plastic. Fire department responded and evacuated the hotel. The hotel was searched for two hours with no results. Fire department went outside and began searching the nearby truck stop for something that may be leaking, when they spotted ammonia trailer. Testing was done with a Drager tube and a reading of 10 ppm was found under the truck. Truck was moved to a separate area and valves were opened in an effort to search for leak. Per Fire Department testing, with a Drager tube, testing resulted in an initial reading of 20 ppm which quickly disappeared. State Police conducted further inspection on the trailer and then released to destination. Further inspection at Massey's Tank facility in Phoenix, AZ, resulted in no leaks found. Report is being filed, but at this point inconclusive as to actual source of odor.
column169: This incident is under further investigation.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported CITX 221071 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top fitting area in the railyard. BNSF contract responders reported finding the T-handled sample line valve open with the closure plug not applied. Responders closed this valve and applied the plug, stopping further product release by 1745 hrs. CDT, 4/28/08. All seals were intact and all other top fittings were found to be secure. Product spillage ran down the sides of CITX 221071 onto the partially frozen ground with some of this spillage evaporating. Absorbent pads were placed atop ground impact area and containment trenches were hand dug on both sides of the yard track were CITX 221071 was standing. On 4/29/08 the ground impact area was water flushed and all liquids (mostly water) were vacuumed up and placed into a 1500 gallon poly tank and earmarked for appropriate disposal.

column168: DSR PAUL FRENDER HAD JUST PICKED UP PRAXAIR AND WAS HEADING TO ANOTHER CUSTOMERS DOCK. AFTER GETTING TO THE CUSTOMERS DOCK HE OPENED THE BACK OF THIS TRAILER AND NOTICES ONE OF THE PORTABLE ROLLING TANKS WAS KNOCKED OVER AND VAPOR WAS DISPERSING FROM THE VALVE. AFTER INSPECTING THE AREA THE DRIVER NOTICED THE ROPE HE USED HAD FRAYED AND SNAPPED. CHEMTRECS WAS CALLED AND INFORMED US TO KEEP THE TRAILER DOOR OPENED TO VENT OUT THE VAPORS. THE TANK DRAINED FOR A DURATION OF ABOUT 15 MINUTES THE TANK DRAINED AND WE WERE TOLD TO RETURN THE TANK TO PRAXAIR TO SWITCH IT OUT.
column169: AFTER SPEAKING TO THE DSR HE DID SECURE THE FREIGHT WITH ROPE TYING TWO TANKS IN AT A TIME SIDE BY SIDE ALONG THE TRAILER WALL AND A LOAD BAR AT THE END TO KEEP FROM SHIFTING TOWARDS THE TRAILER DOOR. THE ROPE FAILED TO HOLD THE FREIGHT IN PLACE IT FRAYED AND THEN SNAPPED MAKING ONE TANK FALL OVER. I MADE SUGGESTIONS SUCH AS CHALKING THE ROLLING TIRES WITH WOOD AND USING OTHER DUNNAGE IF AVAILABLE TO KEEP THE SECURE AND ALSO SUGGESTED KEEPING PORTABLE TANKS ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER TO ACCOMMODATE WITH THE CROWN OF THE ROAD.

column168: On April 17th, 2008 at 09:53 hours, CSXT personnel on local switcher train B74717, while switching at the HK Krevit Company, located at milepost QV 72 on the Amtrak mainline in New Haven, CT, moved PROX 82980, a loaded chlorine tank car, while hooked to an unloading rack. PROX 82980 was in the process of being unloaded, the unloading pipes where ripped from one liquid and one vapor line. The chlorine unloading rack emergency shutdown system operated along with the PROX 82980 liquid line excess flow check valve and an employee of HK Krevit company donned personal protective equipment and closed the liquid and vapor line valves on he tank car. The New Haven Fire Department and Hazardous Material Team responded, and found two railroad employees and eleven personnel at the HK Krevit Company, (six Krevit employees and five outside contractor employees) requested medical treatment for possible chlorine exposure, and two employees from Patient Care Services at Leeway (across the street from the Krevit Company) requested medical treatment. None of the persons treated were hospitalized.  Air monitoring conducted by Connecticut Department of Environmental Protection at the facility found no traces of chlorine vapors inside facility or near the tank car unloading rack. CT-DEP allowed personnel to return to work and allow CSX, FRA and emergency response personnel to review the site and inspect the tank car valves and fittings for proper securement.  PROX 82980 was re-spotted at the unloading rack at 22:30 hours, April 17th, 2008.   Cause Code: 662, 1 Liquid and 1 Vapor valve loading lines pulled out when tank car was moved from unloading spot while connected.  NARRI:  5(5+10+5) X (2+5) = 700
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On April 24th at 13:08 hours while inspecting cars in the CSXT Tilford Yard, FRA Inspector Nancy Hunter discovered ACFX75993, a loaded tank car of Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Organic, N.O.S. dripping product from bottom outlet area.  The area around the rail car was isolated.  Chemtrec (report number 2008-04-24-00181) assisted in contacting the shipper, Stepan Chemical Company.  SWS First Response, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the top operated bottom outlet valve open 1-1/2 turns.  Contractor personnel closed the valve, then removed the bottom outlet cap to drain the nozzle of product.  They also checked the four bolt auxiliary valve bottom outlet mounting flange nuts for proper securement.  The leak was secured and the car released for transport.  Less than one gallon of material was released from the tank car. No special movement was needed.  Cause Code:  100  NARRI = 5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column168: On April 25, 2008, at 18:21 hours, personnel in the CSXT Willard Terminal discovered UTLX 500010, a loaded tank car of toluene leaking from its top. The car was isolated and shipper was notified. CSXT dispatched a response contractor, Eagle Construction + Environmental Services, Inc. (ECESI), Findlay, OH. Upon inspection of UTLX 500010 evidence of a liquid leak was noted on both sides of the tank emanating from within the loading valve protective cover. ECESI personnel broke the seal, and liquid was noted about the threads of the liquid line valve. The liquid line valve appeared closed, i.e. 90 degrees to the valve body, with handle against its stop. ECESI, using an 18 inch pipe, turned the plug for the liquid line valve less than 1/8 turn and the leak ceased. CSXT personnel moved UTLX 500010 to and fro and again insepcted UTLX 500010. ECESI personnel removed the plug for the liquid line valve and noted the entire chamber between the top of the ball valve of the liquid line valve and underside of its plug to be full of toluene. This product was collected by ECESI personnel. CSXT personnel set the car over the spill pan in the Willard Terminal. ECESI returned April 26, 2008 to inspect UTLX 500010. The car was again moved to and fro, and ECESI personnel reported liquid present above the ball valve. Marathon Petroleum Inc. was advised of this, and arranged for delivery of a replacement valve to Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI). SPSI personnel replaced and leak tested of the replacement valve on April 28, 2008 with no exceptions noted. The car was released on April 29, 2008.    5(5 + 3 + 0)  * (2 + 0) = 80  300

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was intransit between the point of origin and the intended truck to truck facility.  Upon arrival at the intended truck to truck facility, it was discovered that a container on the vehicle had leaked allowing approximately 1 gallon of material to be released onto the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel immediately donned appropriate protective equipment and initiated appropriate response procedures.  Upon identification of the damaged container, it was determined that a 55 gallon steel drum had developed a small puncture.  During transportation, the  load movement allowed the liquid to escape.  The response crew collected all spill material using a suitable absorbent material and disposed of it into a 55 gallon drum.  The leaking drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon salvage drum.  The shipment was then transferred into a vehicle to continue on to the intended waste disposal facility.

column168: On April 22, 2008 at 12:20, personnel in the CSXT rail yard in Bainbridge, GA discovered UTLX 201059, a residue tank car of Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S., leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Regional Enterprises, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2008-04-22-00150.  CSXT's trainmaster stopped the release by tightening the bottom outlet valve cap. Absorbent was utilized to absorb any free liquid. Driver contacted General Environmental Management (GEM) dispatch. GEM contacted National Response Center, Washington Emergency Management Department and Washington Department of Ecology. GEM also contacted an outside private hazardous materials spill clean up company to assist in the clean-up. Material was cleaned up, damaged container was overpacked, samples taken and the agencies approved the clean-up. No material entered the stormdrain. The incident was completed by 15:00 the same day. Based upon a photograph of the drum, and on the drum supplier, GEM assumes the following marking is the same marking that was on the drum that released the hazardous material, although the original drum has been shipped for disposal and this cannot be confirmed. UN1A2/Y1.2/100/USA/R1234/08/RL

column62: Inadequate Procedures; Broken Component or Device
column168: The cargo tank had just been filled with anhydrous ammonia (NH3) at the Agrium US, Inc. facility located in North Bend, OH and was proceeding to the scales on the property for weighing when the release occurred.  Approximately 4740 pounds of NH3 liquid escaped from the tank through the damaged pressure relief device as vapor into the atmosphere.  The remaining liquid in the tank auto-refrigerated below the boiling point of NH3 and no additional product was released.  Because of the decisive actions on the scene by another Grammer Industries, Inc. driver, the remaining product was able to be transferred to another cargo tank to prevent further release of the product.      The temperature of the anhydrous ammonia that was loaded in the tank was estimated between 0° and 40° Fahrenheit as evidenced by the frost forming on the tank and associated piping (cold shock see note 5 in 49 CFR 173.315(a)(2)).   The cargo tank was subjected to extreme temperature swings because of this “cold shock” loading.  The differences in the expansion and contraction rates for steel versus aluminum may have contributed to the elongation of the bolted connections and “cold shocking” the trailer would only exacerbate this condition.      The cargo tank was designed with three baffle assemblies.  The rear most baffle assembly’s lower curb side bracket that was attached to the baffle bracket through a bolted connection and attached to cargo tank wall on a pad failed in bending fatigue, resulting in a series of events that ultimately caused the failure of the rear most re-closing pressure relief device.  After the initial failure of the lower curb side bracket, the fore and aft movement of the liquid in the tank created a twisting motion on the upper curb side bracket attachment.  The result was a flexing and swinging motion of the baffle assembly, causing the transfer of high bending stresses and an exaggerated twisting motion to the baffle assembly’s upper (curb side) baffle attachment bracket.  The baffle’s upper bracket then failed primarily due to a combination of bending fatigue and shear type failure.     Once the upper and lower baffle attachment brackets failed, the baffle assembly was then free to “swing” fore and aft with the motion of the liquid in the cargo tank with the driver side upper and lower attachment points acting as hinges on a door.  The repeated contact between the relief valve spring and the baffle assembly eventually led to the failure of the relief stem in the pressure relief device.  The failure of the stem was caused by a bending fatigue crack growth from constant impact of the baffle assembly.  When the stem finally failed, this resulted in the release of liquid anhydrous ammonia to the atmosphere through the failed re-closing pressure device opening in the top of the cargo tank.
column169: 1. Modify the baffles to reduce the possibility that a baffle assembly could make contact with a re-closing pressure relief device if the attachment of the baffle assembly to the cargo tank wall failed.    2. Modify the inspection procedure to include the inspection of the baffle clips, weld attachments and bolt holes and bolted attachments for fatigue cracks, loose bolts or elongated bolt holes.

column168: On April 6th, 2008 at 5:00pm SCA Tissue personal went to unload tanker car HOKX 111394 which contained 50% liquid caustic soda which was shipped by Occidental Chemical Corporation. Following thecompany procedure, the unloader verified that the external ball valve on the bottom of the car and thei nternal tank valve on the car were closed. He then removed the seal plug on the unloading line on the bottom of the car. At this time a small amount of caustic drained out of the unloading line and into a bucket. The unloader noticed that caustic continued to drip out of the line for about one minute. Heverified again that the internal tank valve was closed and noticed that caustic was still dripping. He then replaced the seal plug on the tank car. The only way that caustic could continue to drip was because both the internal valve and the external ball valve leaked passed the seals.In order to safely unload the caustic car, Rescar was called in to install two additional external ball valves to the bottom of the tank car. Using the two new valves, SCA Tissue was able to safely unload the caustic tank car.SCA Tissue was not able to determine the cause of the failure with the valves due to the limited access tothe valves. The tank car will be sent back to Occidental Chemical Corporation for investigation and repair.
column169: Occidental Chemical Corporation was notified of the leaking valves on tank car HOKX 111394. They willtake the tank car back after unloading and repair it

column168: At approxiamtely 4:20 A.M. driver lost control of tanker truck and slid into barrow ditch.  The tank seperated from the cab and came to rest in the ditch. Highway patrol responded and built earthen dams on both end of the ditch and the spilled material was contained within an approximate 300 feet long area in the ditch.  A clean up company repsonded and used a pump truck to recover the free liquids form the ditch.  A more extensive clean up took place in the days that followed the accident and several tons of diesel impacted soil was removed and replaced.  Teh TCEQ and TXDOT were invloved wth all aspects of the clean up.

column168: On April 7, 2008, a Southwest mechanic was assigned to replace a battery on A/C 482. After the mechanic changed out the battery, he placed an unserviceable tag on the used battery and placed it on the forward cargo bin door threshold. At that time, he was called to complete the NAV data and OPC data loads. The Data loader was not working correctly so it required the mechanic to perform a bench load which took longer than expected. When the mechanic completed the data loads, he performed his walk around and did not notice that the battery was still there or that the belt loader had been there. Evidently, the battery was loaded by a ramp agent. When the item was discovered in MOW, the battery was removed and was reported. Safety was then notified of the situation, who inturn, notified the local FAA office.

column168: AFTER FLUSHING APPOX 30 GALLONS TO OFF-COLOR SLOP TANK LOADER SET MICRO MOTION METER TO LOAD 870 GALLONS OF DEISEL INTO #2 COMPARTMENT WITH A CAPACITY OF 900  GALLONS. LOAD WAS STARTED AND COMPARTMENT OVER-FILLED AND SPILLED APPROX 2-3 GALLONS OF DIESEL . LOADER WAS NEXT TO MICROMOTION CONTROLS AND STOPPED TRANSFER. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS FLUSHED INTO PLANT CHEMICAL SEWER. INVESTIGATION FOUND NO PROBLEM WITH MICROMOTION METER BY CALIBRATION AND SUSPECTED NITROGEN BUBBLES CAUSED THE METER TO MISCALCULATE THE METERED VOLUME. INVESTIGATION DID REVEAL THE ENTIRE LINE (APPROX 2500 FT) WAS BLOWN DOWN THE DAY BEFORE FOR A MAINT ACTIVITY WHICH PROBABLY CAUSED THE VAPOR LACKING OF THE METER.
column169: 1. LOAD LARGER COMPARTMENTS FIRST WHRE POSSIBLE 2. SLOW DOWN LOADING BY CONTROLLING LOADING VALVE TO ENSURE ALL N2 GASES HAVE GONE THRU THE LOADING SYSTEM BEFORE OPENING VALVES COMPLETELY.

column168: On April 30, 2008 at 17:07 personnel in the CSXT Philadelphia East Side Yard discovered TILX 120001, a loaded  tank car of Sulfuric Acid, Spent, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Transflo and Marsulex, were notified. Savage, the Transflo contractor, was contacted as well since Savage personnel loaded the car. Savage personnel arrived and found that the liquid line was leaking from the liquid line cap. Savage personnel released the pressure on the car and it was discovered that the treads on the liquid line cap were bad. A new cap was placed on the car and the car was held by CSXT as a Non-Conforming package. Contractor personnel decontaminated the car and cleaned up any spilled material.  Cause Code:  252  NARRI: 5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100    Chemtrec Report # 2008-04-30-00197

column168: Driver was pumping propane from his vehicle to a storage tank.  When finished everything was turned off, shut down, and closed all related implements.  Driver disconnected the liquid hose that is on the vehicle from the storage tank. The hose fell in his hand and started spraying out of the pipe from the storage tank.  The release stopped on its own after approx ½ gas gallon of propane released.
column169: This incident is in the process of being reviewed by our Safety Department.  Any additional training or suggestions are in the process of being made.

column168: Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was delivering a non-DOT specification closed bulk bin designed for the transport of solid/liquid mixtures to the intended waste management facility.  Upon arrival , the driver was instructed to lower the bulk bin from the transport vehicle.  While lovering the bulk bin from the transport vehicle, approximately one gallon of liquid escaped from the top seal of the bulk bin onto an area of soil adjacent to the off-loading area.  Facility personnel immediatley seured the container and proceeded to remove the contaminated soil. All collected spill material was containerized and disposed of along with the contensts of the bulk bin.
column169: The non-secification bulk bin utilized for the transportation of the material in question is designed for the safe transport of liquid solid mixtures (sludges).  At the time of loading, the load was inspected and all closures were intact and no evidence of leakage was observed.  It is believed that upon arrival at the disposal facility, liquid that was incorporated into the sludge at the time of loading separated out of the material and the presence of this liquid and the angle at which the bulk bin was being lowered to the ground allowed a small amount of liquid to pass through the top seal of the package. It is susspected that the cloure loosened slightly during transportation allowing the lquid to pass between the gasket and closure device. In order to prevent a recurrence, drivers will continue to inspect each package accepted for transportation and insure all closures are adequately closed and take all appropriate actions should a closure loosen during transport to prevent an unintentional release.

ONE ADDITIONAL WORKER DID NOT COME IN DIRECT CONTACT WITH THE SUBSTANCE BUT REQUESTED TO BE CHECKED BY THE MEDICAL FACILITY. DOCKWORKER #1 EXPERIENCED IRRITATION TO THE EYES AND THROAT. HE WAS TAKEN TO THE MEDICAL CENTER WHERE HIS VITAL SIGNS WERE CHECKED, HIS EYES WERE FLUSHED AND HE WAS ADVISED TO DRINK WATER. HE HAS SINCE EXPERIENCED NO DISCOMFORT BUT WILL RETURN TO THE CLINIC FOR A FOLLOW-UP VISIT AS A PRECAUTION. NO TIME WAS LOST FROM WORK. NO PPE WAS USED. DOCKWORKER #2 WASHED IMMEDIATELY AFTER CONTACT WITH THE SUBSTANCE AND EXPERIENCED SLIGHT IRRITATION TO HIS THROAT. HIS VITAL  SIGNS ALSO WERE TAKEN AT THE MEDICAL CENTER AND HE WAS TOLD TO DRINK WATER. HE HAS SINCE EXPERIENCED NO DISCOMFORT AND WILL RETURN TO THE CLINIC FOR A FOLLOW-UP VISIT. NO TIME WAS LOST FROM WORK. NO PPE WAS USED. DOCKWORKER #3 DID NOT COME INTO DIRECT CONTACT WITH THE SUBSTANCE BUT WAS WORKING NEARBY. HE REQUESTED TO BE CHECKED AT THE MEDICAL CENTER. HIS VITAL SIGNS WERE MONITORED AND HE WAS RELEASED TO RETURN TO WORK. THERE WAS NO LOST TIME. NO PPE WAS USED.

column168: Our Employee was at a customer location with the purpose of evacuating the tank before the tank could be picked up.  The Customer had an old withdrawal hose attached to the check lock for approx 20 years with the purpose of fueling an agricultural dryer.  When the Employee twisted the withdrawal hose twice, the hose stopped spitting – this made the Employee believe that if the hose was taken off, the safety check inside the check lock would prevent propane from escaping.  The hose was twisted once more and the valve on the check lock did not secure and propane released. There was nothing the employee could do to stop the release.
column169: It has been found that this accident was not preventable.   The spring inside the check lock failed.

column168: ON APRIL 15, 2008, OUR COMPANY, FRATICELLI TRUCKING COMPANY PROGRAMMED A DELIVERY OF SULFURIC ACID. THE ORIGIN WAS INDUSTRIAL CHEMICALS CORPORATION (ICC) AND THE DESTINATION WAS TROPICAL-LOOSE CARGO AREA (TROPICAL). OUR DRIVER, GENOVES SANTIAGO, PICK UP 60 DRUMS OF SULFURIC ACID IN A 40 FEET CONTAINER. BEFORE LEAVING ICC, HE INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND EVERYTHING LOOK IN PLACED. NO SIGNS OF LEAKS OR ANY OTHER ABNORMALLY WERE SEEN. HE LEFT ICC NEAR NOON. OUR DRIVER ARRIVED TO TROPICAL ON THE AFTERNOON, AND HE PARKED THE CONTAINER AT THE UNLOADING GATE. PERSONNEL OF TROPICAL MADE A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER AND SAW A LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER. THEY TOLD THE DRIVER THAT THEY WOULD NOT RECEIVE THE CONTAINER. OUR DRIVER LOOKS FOR A TEMPORARY BUT SAFE PARKING AREA WHILE HE CALLED OUR OFFICE FOR INSTRUCTIONS. OUR DRIVER STOP ON A SECURE AREA CLOSED TO TROPICAL. HE INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AGAIN AND THE LEAKAGE EVENTUALLY RAN OFF. OUR COMPANY SENT CALCIUM CARBONATE TO THE AREA TO ABSORB AND NEUTRALIZE THE ACID. THE LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE DRUM AT THE BOTTOM. THESE DRUM WERE PALLETIZED. A LOOSE NAIL PUNCTURE THE BOTTOM OF A DRUM LOCATED AT THE CENTER OF THE CONTAINER (SEE ADDENDUM A) AND 20 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID WERE SPILLED. AS A RESULT OF THIS BROKEN DRUM, NEITHER HUMAN FATALITIES NOR HUMAN INJURIES OCCURRED. NO ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGES OCCURRED NEITHER. THE MATERIAL SPILLED ON THE PARKING AREA AND ON THE ROAD WAS NEUTRALIZED, RECOLLECTED AND WILL BE DISPOSED PROPERLY. THE WASTE WILL BE DISPOSED BY CLEAN HARBORS (SEE ADDENDUM B). ANY FURTHER INFORMATION RECEIVED FROM CLEAN HARBORS WILL BE SENT AS SOON AS RECEIVED.
column169: IMPROVEMENTS TO PREVENT AND/OR MINIMIZE INCIDENTS RELATED TO THE TRANSPORTATION OF DRUMS: 1. PROTECT DRUM’S BOTTOM FROM PALLETS — ENCOURAGE THE USE OF PALLETS WITHOUT NAILS, OR ALTERNATIVE PALLETS’ MATERIALS THAT ARE ACID RESISTANT. 2. INCREASE COMMUNICATION BETWEEN SHIPPER, TRANSPORTER AND FINAL DESTINATION — HAVE A TELEPHONE COMMUNICATION WITH ALL THE PERSON RESPONSIBLE IS A CASE OF AN EMERGENCY.

On 4/23/08 at 09:00, personnel in the CSX Intermodal Boston Terminal discovered CSXU232341, a loaded intermodal trailer of multiple shippers of Corrosives Class 8 and one item of Oxidizer Class 5.1, leaking Corrosive Class 8 (detergent solutions) from underneath the center of trailer.  The trailer was isolated and rail shipper, All Modes, (Bob 800-601-8100 x105) was notified (CHEMTREC Report  #2008042300182). EMI, a CSX Intermodal  response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found several pails shifting and falling over with one pail leaking approximately 10 gallons.  Contractor personnel transloaded the lading into intermodal trailer CSXU937426, decontaminted the CSXU232341 trailer, and cleaned up the spilled material.  Both trailers were released to the shipper for transportation continuance.  This incident was due to improper blocking, bracing, and loading.

column168: AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT THERE WERE TWO ELECTRICAL SWITCHES THAT HAD TO BE "ON" TO ENERGIZE THE LOADING PUMP AT THE FACILITY. ONE SWITCH WAS AT GROUND LEVEL AND THE OTHER WAS ON/NEAR THE PRODUCT FILL HOSE. THE INTENT WAS TO PREVENT AN UNINTENTIONAL PUMPING OF PRODUCT. THE UNDERSTOOD PROCEDURE IS TO MAKE THE PRODUCT LINE CONNECTIONS ON THE DOME OF THE TRAILER THEN POWER UP THE SWITCH AT GROUND LEVEL; THEN RETURN TO THE TOP OF THE TRAILER AND TURN THE SWITCH ON THE DRIVER POWERED THE SWITCH AT GROUND LEVEL FIRST (BEFORE MAKING THE PRODUCT LINE CONNECTION). WHILE HE WAS MOVING THE FILL HOSE INTO POSITION THERE WAS A MALFUNCTION IN THE SWITCH AND THE PUMP TURNED ON. SPLASHING PRODUCT ONTO THE TRAILER. MOST OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA. HOWEVER, THERE WAS ABOUT 5 GALLONS THAT WAS WASHED OFF OF THE TRAILER AND OUTSIDE OF THE CONTAINMENT AREA. THIS SPILL WAS CLEANED ON THE CUSTOMER'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR. THE FAULTY ELECTRICAL SWITCH WAS REPLACED.

No action contributed to this failure other than the weight of the other bags abraded the botttom bag on the pallet causing the unintentional release. Spilled material was swept up and placed into a recovery container along with the leaking bag.

The consignee was going to unload our cargo tank.  The trailer was pressurized with nitrogen.  When they opened the discharge valves on the trailer, product started to drip from a pinhole leak in the assembly.  The valves were immediately closed.  Product was transferred to another trailer using a pump rather than putting pressure on the line.
column169: When the cargo tank was empty and cleaned, the valve assembly was replaced.

column169: CHECK TRAILER FOR NAILS WHEN LOADING. INSPECT AREAS THOROUGHLY TO ENSURE UNSAFE CONDITIONS ARE NOT PRESENT TO AVOID EASY DAMAGING OR PUNCTURING TO PACKAGES OF DRUMS, PAILS, BAGS AND OTHER PACKAGING CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OR CHEMICALS. PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS Of LIQUIDS. CHECK TRAILER FLOORS AND DOCK AREAS TO ENSURE SHARP EDGES, WOOD PIECES, NAILS ARE NOT PRESENT TO AVOID EASY DAMAGES OR INJURIES. CHEMICAL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED TO PREVENT FROM BEING DAMAGED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT OR SHARP AND POINTED OBJECTS, SUCH AS A NAIL. USE DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD, MTY PALLETS AND OR AIRBAGS TO PROPERLY SHROUD, BLOCK, BRACE AND SECURE FREIGHT AND THE ENTIRE LOAD. RETRAINING IN PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICAL FREIGHT, USING PROPER AND SAFE BLOCKING AND BRACING LOADING TECHNIQUES.

column168: The SOCI driver logged into the truck at 5am Tuesday April 8, 2008. The driver drove to the Marathon Terminal in Canton, OH and loaded 8500 gallons of 87 gasahol. The driver then departed the Canton refinery and proceded westbound on Route 30 and stopped at the Old Airport Road SOCI facility for a tire change. The driver then left and headed westbound on Route 30. After he crossed the Wayne County line and into the Ashland County line he collided with two parked semis. He ripped open the 3500 gallon compartment of his tanker. The driver was disabled and EMS, fire department and State Highway Patrol were called. The fire department sprayed foam on the trucks. K & D were called to contain and clean up the spill.
column169: This incident was caused by the driver having a blood alcohol content of .0675. SOCI Petroleum has decided to increase the percentage of alcohol and drug testing for the fleet to let drivers know we are serious about this problem. We are also going to re-educate all employees regarding drug and alcohol use and abuse in the workplace.

column168: Andrew Gonzales, Director of Track Maintenance, reported receiving a notification from Joe Mejia, Director of Federal Railroad Administration, who advised an FRA Inspector was exposed to a liquid from tank car UTLX 661620, located in the Los Nietos Yard, Santa Fe Springs, CA, Mile Post 4.15 of the Los Nietos Subdivision. Mr. Gonzales advised the inspector closed a leaking valve with his hands and rubbed his eyes. Dean Cooper, Manager, Hazardous Materials, was notified and a conference call was established with Mr. Mejia. Mr. Mejia advised Jack Vail, FRA Inspector, was inspecting a tank car when he heard a hissing noise. He climbed the car and opened the protective valve cover, where he observed a partially opened valve. He was sprayed in the left eye and face. Mr. Mejia advised Inspector Vail immediately washed his face and eye with water and called Mr. Mejia. Mr. Mejia further advised Inspector Vail was driving himself to his personal doctor in Fullerton, and would update RMCC on his condition. Mr. Cooper advised he was en route to the Los Nietos yard to locate and inspect the tank car. At 02:39PM, Manager Cooper advised an inspection developed the FRA Inspector opened the protective valve cover on the top of the tank car, and while closing the open ball valve on the liquid line, it created a build up ot pressure at the pinch point, creating a mist from the product residue on the top of the ball valve that spayed his face. The plug closure for the liquid valve was laying on top of the pressure plate within the protective cover, and not secured on the liquid valve. Manager Cooper stated he properly secured the liquid line valve and plug closure, then inspected the tank car and found no other evidence of release. The tankcar was set out to Yard Track 6 and placed on bad order status so it could be inspected by the car department.
TO BE ENTERED IN QC2 PHASE

column168: The driver had loaded product going to the Enterpise Car Rental at the Bluegrass Airport. Upon arrival, the driver prepared to pump off the load into an above ground tank. He got his hoses hooked up with the safety pins in the pressure hose, he opened all the valves, vents and the tank valve. After all connections were made, the driver engaged the PTO and ran the rpm’s up to 900. He then got out of the truck and was proceeding toward the belly valve area. As he got to the pump, the hose slid off it’s fitting. The driver ran to the PTO and shut down, then to the belly valve and shut down, then to the loading head and shut down and finally the tank valve and shut down. He saw that the hose had a loose clamp. He put the hose back on the fitting to catch any remaining fuel. At that time he called dispatch and started the remediation process immediately.  *The hose used in the pump off was a brand new hose. The hose should have been able to withstand the pressure.  Gra-Kat arrived on site and met with the local fire department. Personnel from Gra-Kat utilized a vacuum truck to collect the material. An asphalt area approx. 300 feet by 3 feet wide had been impacted by the release. The crew deployed granular absorbents to the freestanding fuel, worked them in with brooms, and secured them in a dump truck pending disposal. Material was disposed of at the Central Kentucky Landfill in Georgetown, KY.  At the scene were: Airport Fire, Lexington Haz-Mat, KY EPA and Lexington DEM.  KY EPA-David Leo, KY EPA-Amy Miller, DEM-Steve Jackson, Airport Mgr. of Engineering & Construction-Mark Day.

column168: Occurrence:   Approximately 80 gallons of Jet A fuel spilled from a Crowley tank truck at the McGrath terminal.       What Happened? On Friday, 4/18/08, around 1100 a Crowley employee at McGrath started the Jet fuel truck to warm it up for use later and it ran for about an hour.  The Crowley supervisor came out of the office around 1410 and walked over to the truck to start deliveries, at which time she saw fuel leaking from the truck.  She could not stop the leak, so she placed a bucket under the point where the fuel was running to the ground and then commenced to transfer the fuel to the Crowley truck adjacent to the leaking truck.  Terminal personnel used a barrel pump and an electric pump to recover about 80 gallons of fuel, which was in two barrels on site.  They placed absorbent boom and pad at the perimeter of the puddled fuel.  After all the free liquid was removed, they backed the truck out and placed absorbent pads on the spill area. The spill site is a slab of ice approximately 8' wide and 20' long, where the truck has been parked during the winter.  The ice slab sits below the prevailing grade in the area and is surrounded by snow berms.  They could get very little additional fuel using absorbent pads to wipe the ice.  The response was complete and the area was secured at around 1700.      An incident response team deployed to McGrath the following day.  The team excavated several spots in the snow around the perimeter and used absorbent pads to wick up any fuel at the base of the snow, but got little or nothing.  They drilled through the ice slab and again tried to wick up any fuel that might be lying under the ice, but got little or nothing.      At this point, we consider the clean up to be complete, subject to soil sampling this spring to confirm that indeed no fuel flowed off of or underneath the ice slab during the spill.     Subsequent inspection of the truck revealed that the water drain pipe running from the tank roof gutter down through the product tank and out the bottom of the tank had a crack.  The likely cause was water freezing in the pipe during the spring thaw/freeze cycle, which was unknown to the operating personnel until the spill occurred.
column169: > Park truck in warm storage when possible.  > Keep roof of tank clear of snow and ice.  > Phase out tank trucks with this design.

column168: Our tractor trailer was involved in a 70 MPH head-on collision with another tractor tralier that for unkown reasons had crossed a center median into the path of our truck. On Impact, our truck became fully engulfed in fire from leaking diesel fuel and leaking drums of waste flammable liquids. 98% of all hazardous materials being transported were consumed in the fire. The other truck overturned but did not catch fire and was not transporting any hazardous materials. Neither driver survived the crash.  There were 8055 gallon drums from 22 different shippers on our truck. The majority of the hazardous materials were paint related material.  Many of the drums failed with the initial impact, others failed as a resuft of the intese heat from the fire. The fire burned for approximately 6 hours. Contractor constructed earthen berm to contain any spilling materials. Approximately 200 cubic yards of contaminated soil will be removed for proper disposal.

column168: FILE-08-44 DOT& OMC   SHIPPER-INDIVIDUAL NOT A COMPANY  AWB# ATW 72175644144 ICT    ON 04/30/2008 AT 2236 EST, THE HAZMAT HOTLINE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM THE KANSAS CITY REGIONAL HUB LOCATED AT 435 RIVER PARK DRIVE, KANSAS CITY, KS 66105. BERNIE FROM THE KANSAS CITY REGIONAL HUB REPORTED THAT THEY HAD A LEAKING ENGINE SHIPMENT. THE HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A PLASTIC TOTE CONTAINING AN ENGINE WITH GASOLINE AND OIL INSIDE. DUE TO NO POSITIVE MEANS OF CLOSURE ON THE ENGINE AND THE SHIPMENT BEING NOT BEING DRAINED/PROPLERY PROEPARED FOR TRANSPORTATION, A TOTAL OF 1 GALLON OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO THE KANSAS CITY REGIONAL HUB VIA TRUCK #4124.    THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.    CLEAR OF SCENE: 0205 EST, 05/01/2008.

SPILL TECHNICIANS BILLI MARSH AND CECEILA HICKEY DONNEDPROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING A FUEL ODOR.
